    },
    {
      "id": "df0roEKDbKD5Nr2U_xYLt",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1013,
      "y": 1557,
      "width": 188.49989318847656,
      "height": 100,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "aT",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 534412371,
      "version": 53,
      "versionNonce": 413189363,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1783951984884,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "\n\ntoo much structure\n and opinions.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "\n\ntoo much structure\n and opinions.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "Z7Fp-4Qbboy4aZztcqbEg",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 492,
      "y": 1832,
      "width": 752.5195922851562,
      "height": 275,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "aU",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1732208083,
      "version": 536,
      "versionNonce": 1255639613,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1783952422933,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Constraints -\n    - Intentional limits placed on the protocol\n      so that it's use is limited to it's intended \"domain\", giving\n      the developers clear signals of when something else might be better.\n\n\n- Client Server - server is passive, client must request first\n    - what if the server needs to send a notification? \n- Stateless Message Passing - \n    - every request has to contain everything the server needs to process it.\n    - No \"state\" is maintained in the server between requests.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Constraints -\n    - Intentional limits placed on the protocol\n      so that it's use is limited to it's intended \"domain\", giving\n      the developers clear signals of when something else might be better.\n\n\n- Client Server - server is passive, client must request first\n    - what if the server needs to send a notification? \n- Stateless Message Passing - \n    - every request has to contain everything the server needs to process it.\n    - No \"state\" is maintained in the server between requests.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "Ue93oq4Ab5C1YIJPsiYbb",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1032,
      "y": 914,
      "width": 1031.33935546875,
      "height": 725,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "aV",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 62579347,
      "version": 1618,
      "versionNonce": 886351901,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1783953272997,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Http responses always should have the same \"shape\"\n- Give the consumer a connection to your database.\n    - you create a denormalized version of your database that you \"sync\" and other services can query it.\n\n- ODATA - Microsoft thing, it's a standard, not very popular, but you'll see it around.\n    - basically adds query to HTTP - mostly through implemented query parameters\n\n- GraphQl - Another approach at this - I really like it, but as an extension to http it loses\nsome important things - like caching, etc. \n\n\n- gRPC - \n    - this sits above HTTP/2 - (which adds connected states) and allows\n      you to use multiple \"models\" of communication\n        - client/server - like HTTP, make a request, wait a response.\n        - client streaming - the client opens a connection to the server, it stays open, the client\n          can stream data asynchronously over time without having to open a connection again.\n          (used a lot in observability, OTEL, etc.)\n        - server streaming - client opens a connection, the server can push data to the client whenever.\n        - \"unity' - client and server streaming.\n\n\n- Inside a web browser \"escaping\" http is usually:\n    - Websockets - bi-directional, message passing. Connected.\n        - microsoft SignalR is GREAT for this on the server (and client, they have a js library)\n    - .NET 10 - Finally built-in support for SSE (Server Sent Events)\n        - this is just sending data from the server to a connected client.\n        - the client (browser) uses HTTP requests for communication.\n    ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Http responses always should have the same \"shape\"\n- Give the consumer a connection to your database.\n    - you create a denormalized version of your database that you \"sync\" and other services can query it.\n\n- ODATA - Microsoft thing, it's a standard, not very popular, but you'll see it around.\n    - basically adds query to HTTP - mostly through implemented query parameters\n\n- GraphQl - Another approach at this - I really like it, but as an extension to http it loses\nsome important things - like caching, etc. \n\n\n- gRPC - \n    - this sits above HTTP/2 - (which adds connected states) and allows\n      you to use multiple \"models\" of communication\n        - client/server - like HTTP, make a request, wait a response.\n        - client streaming - the client opens a connection to the server, it stays open, the client\n          can stream data asynchronously over time without having to open a connection again.\n          (used a lot in observability, OTEL, etc.)\n        - server streaming - client opens a connection, the server can push data to the client whenever.\n        - \"unity' - client and server streaming.\n\n\n- Inside a web browser \"escaping\" http is usually:\n    - Websockets - bi-directional, message passing. Connected.\n        - microsoft SignalR is GREAT for this on the server (and client, they have a js library)\n    - .NET 10 - Finally built-in support for SSE (Server Sent Events)\n        - this is just sending data from the server to a connected client.\n        - the client (browser) uses HTTP requests for communication.\n    ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
